Implement the following plan:

# Plan: Fix crash on HTML fragment input

## Context

Readability's `_grabArticle` walks up the DOM via `parentNode` until it finds a
node whose `tagName === "BODY"`. In linkedom, walking past the document root
returns `null`, not a `<body>` element. So when the input is an **HTML fragment**
(no `<html>`/`<body>` wrapper — as returned by the Confluence REST API's
`body.export_view`), Readability hits `null.tagName` and crashes:

```
TypeError: Cannot read properties of null (reading 'tagName')
    while (parentOfTopCandidate.tagName !== "BODY")
```

The fix: normalise the input to always be a full HTML document before parsing.

## Fix

**`src/extract.ts` — `parseDocument()` (line 60)**

Wrap the HTML in a minimal shell if it isn't already a full document:

```ts
export function parseDocument(html: string): Document {
  const normalised = /^\s*<(!DOCTYPE|html)/i.test(html)
    ? html
    : `<html><body>${html}</body></html>`;
  return parseHTML(normalised).document;
}
```

The regex check is cheap: a full page starts with `<!DOCTYPE` or `<html>`.
Anything else is treated as a fragment and wrapped. This is the right place
because `parseDocument` is the single entry point for all HTML into the pipeline.

No changes needed to `mod.ts`, `cli.ts`, or any other `src/` file.

## Tests to add in `mod_test.ts`

```ts
const FRAGMENT_HTML = `
<h1>Fragment Heading</h1>
<p>Some <strong>content</strong> here.</p>
`;

Deno.test("reader mode: handles HTML fragment without crashing", () => {
  const { markdown } = convert(FRAGMENT_HTML, { frontmatter: false });
  assertStringIncludes(markdown, "Fragment Heading");
});

Deno.test("full mode: handles HTML fragment without crashing", () => {
  const { markdown } = convert(FRAGMENT_HTML, {
    frontmatter: false,
    reader: false,
  });
  assertStringIncludes(markdown, "Fragment Heading");
});
```

## Files to modify

- `src/extract.ts` — `parseDocument()`, 3-line change
- `mod_test.ts` — add `FRAGMENT_HTML` constant + 2 tests

## Verification

```bash
deno task test
echo "<h1>Hello</h1><p>World</p>" | deno run --allow-read --allow-env cli.ts
```


